  "text": "Calcium has not been considered of etiological importance in cancer for many years. However, several studies have suggested that dietary calcium may be associated with a reduced risk of colon cancer. [CITATION_1] Calcium may bind with fats in the intestine, making fats less accessible to metabolism by bile salts and the subsequent formation of carcinogenic breakdown products. [CITATION_2] Fenech and Bonassi 54 showed a decrease in MN frequency related to calcium intake. Our results are not consistent with most epidemiologic literature as we have found a positive correlation between calcium and MN, but we corroborate Smith et al [CITATION_3] who also found that high calcium intake was associated with higher levels of MN.",
